This seems very similar to `Finset.prod_range_div`. Do you think you can use that instead?
`Finset.prod_range_div` assume `CommGroup`, but I suppose I could change this lemma to use `/`.
Well actually, this lemma isn't quite the right way around to use `/`.
I've shuffled things around to use `/`, but of course I still can't use `Finset.prod_range_div` directly.
Does the `commutatorMap` deserve to be factored into a standalone definition?
Could you please add, for convenience, the corollaries that `G` is abelian, and has odd order (or no elements of order 2, or both)?

I think this should not be in the `MulEquiv` namespace. But I'm not sure in which namespace it *should* be... `Function` is bad, because in that context the function really not have any fixed points. `MulHom`? `MonoidHom`?
Maybe we should ask on zulip.
`MonoidHom` seems most natural to me (the `MulEquiv` was just a holdover from when I had to state several of the theorems in terms of `MulEquiv`)
(`MonoidHom` seems better than `MulHom` since the whole point is that `1` is special).

This is a term, not a type, so
```suggestion
def commutatorMap [Div G] (g : G) := g / Ï† g
```
